<paragraph pageNumber="33">
This monotypic genus is distributed in the upper Amazon basin, including the Ucayali, Purus, and 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Mamoré">Mamore</normalizedToken>
River drainages.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="34">
<taxonomicName genus="Planiloriaria" pageNumber="34" rank="genus">
<pageStartToken pageNumber="34">Planiloriaria</pageStartToken>
</taxonomicName>
inhabits sandy substrates in the main streams of large rivers (Evers &amp; Seidel 2005). Reproductive ecology is unknown but could be reminiscent of those of other representatives of the 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:E805457A-B6F3-4756-950E-1AD4B96002BB" class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Pseudohemiodon" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Pseudohemiodon Bleeker 1862:3" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="34" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Pseudohemiodon</taxonomicName>
group. Evers &amp; Seidel (2005) characterized sexual dimorphism by the shape of the genital area. The genital area in males is elongate and narrow compared with the large and roundish area of females. 
<taxonomicName LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:704E46E2-FF8D-438E-A9B1-8AD1A5354D67" class="Actinopterygii" family="Loricariidae" genus="Planiloricaria" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Planiloricaria Pseudohemiodon Isbrücker 1971:276" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="34" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Planiloricaria</taxonomicName>
shows derived features such as a reduction in size and number of teeth, premaxillary teeth absent, a circular head shape, and eyes reduced in size without iris operculum.
</paragraph>
